%I A084451 #24 Apr 17 2026 14:33:38
%S A084451 7,11,13,14,7,19,25,28,14,7,35,21,26,13,22,11,37,50,25,44,22,11,69,38,
%T A084451 19,41,52,26,13,70,35,49,56,28,14,7,67,97,112,56,28,14,7,131,73,100,
%U A084451 50,25,76,38,19,137,84,42,21,74,37,82,41,148,74,37,146,73,164,82,41,276
%N A084451 Juggling states associated with the juggling sequence A084452.
%C A084451 Start with a(0) = 7, and then set a(n+1) = a(n)/2 if a(n) is even, otherwise a(n+1) = (a(n)-1)/2 + 2^e for the smallest e such that a(n+1) has no earlier occurrence in the sequence and is a term of A014311. - _Antti Karttunen_, Apr 17 2026
%H A084451 Antti Karttunen, <a href="/A084451/b084451.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..12087</a>
%H A084451 A. Karttunen, <a href="/A084507/a084507.scm.txt">Scheme-program for computing this sequence</a>
%H A084451 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Siteswap.html">Siteswap</a>
%H A084451 <a href="/index/Bi#binary">Index entries for sequences related to binary expansion of n</a>.
%F A084451 a(0)=7, a(n) = (a(n-1) + 2^A084452(n) - 1)/2.
%e A084451 a(0) = 7 by definition.
%e A084451 a(1) = (a(0)-1)/2 + 2^e = 3 + 2^e, but e=0 or 1 cannot be used as 4 and 5 have less than three 1-bits, while e=2 cannot be used because 3+4 = 7 is already present in the sequence, so the next smallest e is 3, thus a(1) = 3 + 2^3 = 11.
%e A084451 a(2) = (a(1)-1)/2 + 2^e = 5 + 2^e, but e=0 cannot be used as 6 has less than three 1-bits, while e=1 cannot be used because 5+2 = 7 is already present in the sequence, so the next smallest e is 3, thus a(2) = 5 + 2^3 = 13.
%e A084451 a(3) = (a(2)-1)/2 + 2^e = 6 + 2^e, but e=0 cannot be used as 6+1 = 7 has already occurred in the sequence, and with e=1..2 the sum has less than three 1-bits, so the next smallest e is 3, thus a(3) = 6 + 2^3 = 14.
%e A084451 a(4) = a(3)/2 = 7. Note that now the previously occurring 7 is allowed, because it is a result of dividing the previous term (that is even) by two.
%Y A084451 Cf. A084449 (positions of sevens, i.e., ground states), A084450 (this sequence in binary), A084452.
%Y A084451 Cf. A395048 (odd terms), A395048 (their indices in this sequence).
%Y A084451 Only terms of A014311 occur here.
%Y A084451 Cf. A084457 for a completely injective variant.
%K A084451 nonn,base
%O A084451 0,1
